  "prompt": "What traffic laws in Martinique are particularly hard for foreign drivers to get used to?",
  "response": "While Martinique shares many traffic laws with mainland France (due to being an overseas territory), there are a few aspects that can be particularly tricky for foreign drivers to adjust to:\n\n*   **Roundabouts (Ronds-Points):** Martinique has a LOT of roundabouts.  While the general rule is to yield to traffic already *in* the roundabout, the **complexity and speed of traffic, especially in Fort-de-France**, can be intimidating.  Drivers need to be very decisive about their exit and use their indicators clearly. Expect drivers to be very aggressive in entering the roundabout even if they are not clearly able to enter, and expect them to be going much faster than what you may expect.\n\n*   **Priorit\u00e9 \u00e0 droite (Priority from the Right):** This is a classic French rule that often trips up tourists. Unless otherwise indicated by signs (yield, stop, or priority), vehicles coming from the right have the right-of-way. This means that at unmarked intersections, you must yield to vehicles approaching from the right, even if you are on what appears to be a larger road. While less common in very urban areas, it's prevalent in smaller towns and rural areas.\n\n*   **Road Markings and Signage:** While road signs are generally in French, many are standard European signs and easily understandable. However, faded or missing road markings can be a problem, particularly lane markings on narrower roads.\n\n*   **Driving Style:** Martinique drivers can be assertive and sometimes impatient. Tailgating, sudden lane changes, and aggressive merging are not uncommon, particularly in and around Fort-de-France.\n\n*   **Narrow Roads:** Many roads, especially in the mountainous interior and along the coast, are very narrow, winding, and lack shoulders. These require careful driving and can be challenging for those used to wider roads. Be prepared to yield to oncoming traffic, especially buses and trucks.\n\n*   **Scooters and Motorbikes:** Scooters and motorbikes are very common in Martinique, and drivers may weave in and out of traffic. Be extra cautious when changing lanes or making turns.\n\n*   **Parking:** Parking can be difficult to find in urban areas, especially Fort-de-France. Pay attention to parking signs and meters to avoid fines. Parking regulations are strictly enforced.\n\n**Here's a breakdown of why these are difficult:**\n\n*   **Roundabouts:** Foreign drivers struggle with the speed, volume, and sometimes aggressive merging tactics.\n*   **Priorit\u00e9 \u00e0 droite:** It's counter-intuitive to many drivers from countries where the larger road usually has priority.\n*   **Narrow Roads:** Requires careful maneuvering, especially when encountering larger vehicles on tight curves.\n*   **Driving Style:** Can be stressful for those used to a more relaxed driving environment.\n\n**Tips for Foreign Drivers:**\n\n*   **Drive defensively:** Expect the unexpected and be prepared to yield even when you think you have the right-of-way.\n*   **Be patient:** Don't get drawn into aggressive driving.\n*   **Plan your route:** Use a GPS or map to familiarize yourself with the route.\n*   **Rent a smaller car:** A smaller car will be easier to maneuver on narrow roads.\n*   **Pay attention to signs:** Learn basic French traffic signs.\n*   **Consider driving during off-peak hours:** Avoid rush hour in Fort-de-France if possible.\n*   **Take your time:** Don't rush, especially on winding roads.\n*   **Honk your horn:** Its use is more socially acceptable than in the USA, for example, when entering blind corners on mountain roads.\n\nBy being aware of these potential challenges and driving defensively, foreign drivers can have a safe and enjoyable experience driving in Martinique.\n",
